00:03:10:110000.Speaker: Raj

00:03:18:030000.Speaker: Howard

00:03:28:070000.Speaker: Raj
00:03:28:070000.Dialogue: I suppose you could have your android penis circumcised.

00:03:33:210000.Speaker: Raj
00:03:33:210000.Dialogue: But that's something your rabbi would have to discuss with the manufacturer.

00:03:37:140000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:03:37:140000.Dialogue: Not to mention you'd have to power down on saturdays.

00:03:42:100000.Speaker: Leonard
00:03:42:100000.Dialogue: Sheldon, why is this letter in the trash?

00:03:44:200000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:03:44:200000.Dialogue: Well, there's always the possibility that a trash can spontaneously formed around the letter but Occam's rasor would suggest that someone threw it out.

00:03:53:230000.Speaker: Leonard
00:03:53:230000.Dialogue: It's from the Institute of Experimental Physics, they want us to present our paper on the properties of supersolids at the topical conference of Bose-Einstein condensates.

00:04:02:110000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:04:02:110000.Dialogue: I know. I read it before I threw it out.

00:04:06:070000.Speaker: Leonard
00:04:06:070000.Dialogue: Ok, if I may drill down to the bedrock of my question: why did you throw it out?

00:04:10:010000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:04:10:010000.Dialogue: Because I have no interest in standing in the Rose room of the Pasadena Marriot, in front of a group of judgmental strangers who wouldn't recognise true genius if it was standing in front of them giving a speech.

00:04:20:150000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:04:20:150000.Dialogue: Which if I were there, would be.

00:04:23:120000.Speaker: Howard
00:04:23:120000.Dialogue: I don't know Sheldon. Those topical conferences on Bose-Einstein condensates' parties are legendary

00:04:34:080000.Speaker: Leonard
00:04:34:080000.Dialogue: Are there any other honours I've got that I don't know about? Did the UPS dropped off a Nobel prize with my name on it?

00:04:40:040000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:04:40:040000.Dialogue: Leonard, please don't take this the wrong way, but the day you win a Nobel prize, is the day I begin my research on the drag coefficient of tassles on flying carpets.

00:04:49:160000.Speaker: Raj
00:04:49:160000.Dialogue: The only thing missing from that insult was: your mama.

00:04:53:230000.Speaker: Howard
00:04:53:230000.Dialogue: I got one... Hey Leonard, Your mama's research methodology is so flawed...

00:04:59:160000.Speaker: Leonard
00:04:59:160000.Dialogue: Sheldon, we have to do this.

00:05:09:150000.Speaker: Leonard
00:05:09:150000.Dialogue: Ok, let me put it this way: I'm doing it.

00:05:11:180000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:05:11:180000.Dialogue: You can't. I'm the lead author.

00:05:14:040000.Speaker: Leonard
00:05:14:040000.Dialogue: Come on, the only reason you're the lead author is because we went alphabetically.

00:05:17:200000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:05:17:200000.Dialogue: I let you think we went alphabetically to spare you the humiliation with dealing with the fact that it was my idea. Now to put too fine a point to it, but I was throwing you a bone.

00:05:28:080000.Speaker: Leonard
00:05:28:080000.Dialogue: Excuse me, I designed the experiment that proved the hypothesis.

00:05:33:230000.Speaker: Leonard
00:05:33:230000.Dialogue: So the entire scientific community is just supposed to take your word?

00:05:37:090000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:05:37:090000.Dialogue: They're not supposed to, but they should.

00:05:40:100000.Speaker: Leonard
00:05:40:100000.Dialogue: Alright, I don't care what you say. I'm going to the conference and I'm presenting our findings

00:05:48:100000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:05:48:100000.Dialogue: If I'm not taking credit for our work then nobody is.

00:05:51:010000.Speaker: Leonard
00:05:51:010000.Dialogue: So, you admit that it's our work.

00:05:56:050000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:05:56:050000.Dialogue: And once again, you are welcome.

00:09:19:070000.Dialogue: Oh, you know, that is so weird that yours came and mine didn't.

00:09:34:040000.Speaker: Penny
00:09:34:040000.Dialogue: Yep. Tip you waitresses. I'm here all week.

00:09:39:170000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:09:39:170000.Dialogue: Penny, just to save you from further awkwardness, know that I'm perfectly comfortable with the two of us climbing the stairs in silence.

00:09:45:150000.Speaker: Penny
00:09:45:150000.Dialogue: Oh, yeah ok, me too. Zip it, lock it. Put it in your pocket.

00:10:01:200000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:10:01:200000.Dialogue: A little misunderstanding... ? Galileo and the Pope had a little misunderstanding.

00:10:10:040000.Speaker: Penny
00:10:10:040000.Dialogue: Anyway, I was talking to Leonard this morning and I think he feels really bad about it. How do you feel?

00:10:21:230000.Speaker: Penny
00:10:21:230000.Dialogue: I'm just asking if it's difficult to be fighting with your best friend.

00:10:26:170000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:10:26:170000.Dialogue: I haven't thought about it like that. I wonder if I've been experiencing physiological manifestations of some sort of unconscious emotional turmoil

00:10:43:080000.Speaker: Penny
00:10:43:080000.Dialogue: You should just talk to him, I'm sure you guys can work this out.

00:10:53:110000.Speaker: Penny
00:10:53:110000.Dialogue: You absolutely should talk to him. Look, I know Leonard values you as a friend and he told me himself without your little idea there's no way he could come up with this whole experiment thing.

00:11:08:050000.Speaker: Penny
00:11:08:050000.Dialogue: Yeah, I mean he tried to explain it to me, I didn't really understand it but..

00:11:10:020000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:11:10:020000.Dialogue: Of course you didn't. He said: Little idea?

00:11:14:230000.Speaker: Penny
00:11:14:230000.Dialogue: Oh, well, no... Not... Not in those words.

00:11:19:150000.Speaker: Penny
00:11:19:150000.Dialogue: Oh, you know... Gee. The exact words are... It's more the spirit in which he said...

00:11:26:230000.Speaker: Leonard
00:11:26:230000.Dialogue: Hey, Sheldon, I've been thinking, instead of arguing about this...

00:11:29:060000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:11:29:060000.Dialogue: Don't you ever speak to me again.

00:11:47:230000.Speaker: Leonard
00:11:47:230000.Dialogue: Ok, I'm leaving for the conference.

00:11:50:090000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:11:50:090000.Dialogue: Have fun presenting my lucky hunch

00:11:52:200000.Speaker: Leonard
00:11:52:200000.Dialogue: Shel, I didn't mean it like that.

00:11:54:160000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:11:54:160000.Dialogue: Then why did you say it?

00:11:56:110000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:11:56:110000.Dialogue: Were you trying to impress Penny?

00:12:01:120000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:12:01:120000.Dialogue: How did that work out for you?

00:12:09:220000.Speaker: Leonard
00:12:09:220000.Dialogue: Ok, I'm gonna ask you one more time. We did the work together, let's present the paper together.

00:12:13:230000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:12:13:230000.Dialogue: And I'm telling you for the last time, it's pandering, it's undignifying, and bite me.

00:13:05:160000.Dialogue: A joke... Ok. How about this? Um, ok... There's this farmer and he has these chickens but they won't lay any eggs, so... He calls a physicist to help. The physicist then does some calculations, and he says: I have a solution, but it only works for spherical chickens in a vacuum.

00:13:31:210000.Speaker: Leonard

00:13:37:170000.Speaker: penny

00:13:45:010000.Speaker: Penny
00:13:45:010000.Dialogue: I really should have brought my own car.

00:13:50:020000.Speaker: Leonard
00:13:50:020000.Dialogue: So, in conclusion, the data show that at temperatures approaching absolute zero, the moment of inertia changes, and a solid becomes a supersolid, which clearly appears to be a previously unknown state of matter. Thank you!

00:14:19:200000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:14:19:200000.Dialogue: Doctor Sheldon Cooper here, I am the lead author of this particular paper. Thank you.

00:14:29:030000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:14:29:030000.Dialogue: And you sir, you have completely skipped over the part where I was walking through the park and I saw these children on a merry-go-round which started me thinking about the moment of inertia in gases like helium at temperatures approaching absolute zero.

00:14:42:000000.Speaker: Leonard
00:14:42:000000.Dialogue: I didn't skip it. It's just an anecdote, it's not science.

00:14:44:220000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:14:44:220000.Dialogue: Oh, I see. It was the apple falling on Newton's head, was that just an anecdote?

00:14:50:180000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:14:50:180000.Dialogue: No, no, that's true. Gravity would have been apparent to me without the apple.

00:14:54:200000.Speaker: Leonard
00:14:54:200000.Dialogue: You cannot possibly be that arrogant.

00:14:56:160000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:14:56:160000.Dialogue: You continue to underestimate me, my good man.

00:14:59:150000.Speaker: Leonard
00:14:59:150000.Dialogue: Look, if you weren't happy with my presentation then maybe you should have given it with me!

00:15:03:120000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:15:03:120000.Dialogue: As I have explained repeatedly, unlike you, I don't need validation from lesser minds. No offense.

00:15:09:100000.Speaker: Leonard
00:15:09:100000.Dialogue: Really, so why did you come?

00:15:10:150000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:15:10:150000.Dialogue: Because I knew you'd screw this up.

00:15:13:110000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:15:13:110000.Dialogue: Oh, please. I admit that spherical chicken joke, that was hilarious.  But it was straight downhill from there.

00:15:19:000000.Speaker: Leonard
00:15:19:000000.Dialogue: I've had enough of your condescendship. Maybe I didn't go to college when I was 11 like you. Maybe I got my doctorate at 24 instead of 16 but you are not the only person who is smarter than everyone else in this room! No offense.

00:15:34:210000.Speaker: Leonard
00:15:34:210000.Dialogue: And I am clearly not the only person who is tormented by insecurity and has an ego in need of constant validation!

00:15:40:160000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:15:40:160000.Dialogue: So you admit you're an egotist?

00:15:42:120000.Speaker: Leonard
00:15:42:120000.Dialogue: Yes! My name is doctor Leonard Hofstadter and I can never please my parents so I need all my self esteem from strangers like you! But he's worse!

00:15:56:170000.Speaker: Leonard
00:15:56:170000.Dialogue: You cannot blow up my head with your mind!

00:15:59:130000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:15:59:130000.Dialogue: Then I'll settle for your aneurism!

00:16:04:210000.Speaker: Leonard
00:16:04:210000.Dialogue: You tried to blow up my head!

00:16:07:070000.Speaker: Leonard
00:16:07:070000.Dialogue: It wa... It was not! You're a nutcase!

00:16:09:160000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:16:09:160000.Dialogue: We'll see about that! Heads up, you people in the front row! This is a splash zone!

00:16:22:070000.Speaker: Penny
00:16:22:070000.Dialogue: Is this usually how these physics things go?

00:16:42:200000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:16:42:200000.Dialogue: You could have offered me a ride home.

00:16:46:130000.Speaker: Leonard
00:16:46:130000.Dialogue: You're lucky I didn't run you over.

00:16:49:100000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:16:49:100000.Dialogue: I really don't understand what you're so unhappy about. You begged me to come, I came. There's just no pleasing you.

00:16:55:040000.Speaker: Leonard
00:16:55:040000.Dialogue: You're right, I'm the problem, I'm the one that needs help.

00:16:58:050000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:16:58:050000.Dialogue: Well, that's not much of an apology but I'll take it.

00:17:01:140000.Speaker: Leonard
00:17:01:140000.Dialogue: Excuse me, is there anything you would apologise for?

00:17:07:050000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:17:07:050000.Dialogue: Yes. I'm sorry I tried to blow up your head.

00:17:16:150000.Speaker: Raj
00:17:16:150000.Dialogue: Somebody got the whole thing with their cell phone and put it on YouTube!

00:17:27:000000.Speaker: Howard
00:17:27:000000.Dialogue: Hey, check it out, it's a featured video!

00:17:28:200000.Speaker: Leonard
00:17:28:200000.Dialogue: He hit me! You saw that he hit me! Oh, Jeez. does this suit really look that bad?

00:17:57:140000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:17:57:140000.Dialogue: Forget your suit, look at my arms waving. I'm like a flamingo on Ritalin.

00:18:04:050000.Speaker: Penny
00:18:04:050000.Dialogue: Howard, would you like to explain to me why your Facebook page has a picture of me sleeping on your shoulder captioned me and my girlfriend?

00:18:13:150000.Speaker: Howard
00:18:13:150000.Dialogue: Uh oh, here comes the talk.
